an></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q43 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Chairman:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We are in a rather bigger room than usual and you look rather a long way away.  I hope that does not make any difference to the way we conduct ourselves.  Let me first of all say I am not the Chairman of the Committee, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">al</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">though some will remember that for many years I was.  Lord MacGregor is away today so I have been asked to take the Chair instead.  I know the familiar faces down there and you know the routine very well.  We are delighted to see you</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Mr Haskew, Ms Barbour and Mr Roy-Chowdhury.  I do not know whether you want to make an opening statement, or do we g</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">o straight into the questions?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Frank Haskew: </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Straight into the questions.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Chairman:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> If I should be the one to start, then, have you been able to review the report on partnerships published recently by the Office of Tax Simplification?  If so, can you give us your initial reactions to that?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Chas Roy-Chowdhury</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">: I have been on the OTS panel looking at partnerships, so I will start with a preamble.  I looked at the draft in a lot of detail, and I </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">have </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">probably not been through </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the final version </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">in as much detail as I would like.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ACCA</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, as an organisation, will make a separate submission.  A lot of work has gone into the report.  As it says on page 13, there have been 50 meetings around the country.  Various groups have been consulted.  It is an interim report and has been categorised into quick fixes, medium-term and long-term.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">long-term</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> category</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, and I know we will come on to this later on, I would be very keen to see the LLP legislation incorporated in.  We would perhaps look at a much more holistic report at the end of the day on partnerships.  One of the problems </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">we had in the OTS committee is that the LLP draft legislation only came out </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">when </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">the final report was about to be produced.  I know it says in the interim report that it was not within </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">its </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">remit, but it could not have been in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">its </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">remit because the legislation was not available at the time.  That is something we probably need to pan</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">out and look at more later on.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">In terms of the timetable, the OTS is going to be looking </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">at other aspects </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">of partnership</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">late</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">r this year</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, if it is allowed to continue.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">here is an election next year, so we are probably looking at legislation</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">in 2016</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">at the earliest</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">.  Within that time, we probably have enough time to look at the current proposals on LLPs, et cetera.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Frank Haskew: </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">I very much concur with what</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Chas has just said.  As you know, the OTS report came out </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">at </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">pretty much the same time.  Our initial view is that the OTS, as </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">it has </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">consistently done, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">has</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> made some very telling, useful and helpful contributions about the way the tax system can be simplified.  It could be seen </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">as their being </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">let down somewhat by the fact that we have </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">g</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">overnment policy going on in parallel, at the same time.  It makes it very difficult when you have almost a twin-track approach.  Really, we need to bring it all together and have one consistent approach.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Charlotte Barbour: </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">ICAS is in a similar position</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">We worked</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">with John Whiting.  He came to meet a lot of our members and we were really pleased with the conversations.  They were robust; they were interesting.  A lot of our members</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">’ concerns</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> have come into the OTS report.  We are really pleased to see that.  In the short term, that may be refocusing HMRC activities and how we support partnerships.  To remember they are not the forgotten partner would be helpful.  In policy terms, it would be nice to see a bigger picture, and we concur </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">on </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">doing everything collectively in one place, rather than piecemeal.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q44 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lord Rowe-Beddoe:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">The draft legislation does not impose the general partnership law tests to determine whether a member of an LLP is a partner or an employee for tax purposes.  It said </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">it produces some detailed mechanical tests.  Could it not have been simpler, is the question, and more coherent to have extended the general partnership law rules to LLPs?  Why did you think the Government chose not to?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Frank Haskew: </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">That is quite an interesting question.  I do not think it is very clear why they went down that route.  The original May 2013 consultation effectively talked about using the existing tests.  Somewhere along the line, it seems as though that view was changed in favour of these totally different tests.  We would still question whether the fundamental basis</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> for the way the Government have </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">approached this is correct.  Section 4.4 of the Limited Liability Partnerships Act talk</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> in terms of a member of an LLP being treated as a partner.  It then go</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">es</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> on to say</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">if they were treated as an employee under the existing partnership rules, that would still apply.  On the face of it, you would say </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">the LLP rules and the existing partnership rules are pretty much coherent, and I still do not think we have had a satisfactory answer as to why it seems </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">that is not regarded as the case.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Charlotte Barbour</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">: There certainly has not been any kind of discussion of it.  It was mentioned briefly in the initial consultation paper last May.  It discussed, much as Frank has, the differences between partnership and limited liability partnership, and that members of an LLP should be treated as a partner.  I suppose the only difference there is that you do have limited liability.  My reading of it is that perhaps</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">draft</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> the tests of what is or is not an employee or disguised employee is quite difficult, allowing for the limited liability.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Chas Roy-Chowdhury</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">: I fully agree with Frank and Charlotte.  One of the key reasons, I guess, behind why we have the three tests is to create no requirement for clearance, uncertainty or ambiguity for self-assessment purposes.  So, yes, it probably helps the HMRC and the Treasury, but at the same time it seems as though the Treasury thought of these tests outside the consultation.  They did not appear anywhere in the consultation.  Looking at the consultation again for the purposes of today, the three tests appeared from left field.  I am not sure other than for certainty why these tests appeared, or how they were devised.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Lord Rowe-Beddoe:</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> Is it right that the original policy aim was to place members of LLPs in the same position for tax purposes as a partner in a general partnership?  Would you agree with that?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:200%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span sty